    <article class="prose dark:prose-invert max-w-none">
      <h2>How to Convert CSV to PDF</h2>
      <p>
        Paste your CSV data into the text area or click the upload button to load a .csv file from your computer. Select the delimiter that matches your data format, and check or uncheck the header row option depending on whether your first row contains column names. The tool parses the data immediately and shows a table preview so you can verify that columns are aligned correctly. Once everything looks right, click "Download PDF" to get a formatted PDF table saved to your device.
      </p>
      <p>
        The converter handles quoted fields, embedded commas, and multi-line values within quotes following the RFC 4180 specification. If your CSV uses a delimiter other than commas, switch the dropdown to tab, semicolon, or pipe before the tool parses. The preview shows up to 20 rows with alternating row shading so you can confirm the structure before committing to a download.
      </p>

      <div class="my-6"><%= render "shared/ad_slot", slot: "in_content" %></div>

      <h2>CSV to PDF for Reporting and Sharing</h2>
      <p>
        Spreadsheet data often needs to leave the spreadsheet. Board members expect a polished PDF attachment, not a raw CSV file they have to open in Excel. Clients receiving an invoice want a printable document, not a comma-separated string. Regulatory filings frequently require PDF submissions even when the source data lives in a database or CSV export. Converting CSV to PDF transforms raw data into a presentation-ready document without requiring you to open a spreadsheet application, manually adjust column widths, or fight with print settings.
      </p>
      <p>
        This tool creates tables with formatted header rows, consistent column widths calculated from the data, and alternating row colors that make dense tables scannable. The PDF automatically paginates when the table exceeds a single page, repeating column headers on each new page so the reader never loses context. These details matter when the document will be printed, projected in a meeting, or attached to a formal communication.
      </p>

      <h3>Creating Printable Data Tables</h3>
      <p>
        Printing CSV data directly produces output that is difficult to read: columns run together, text wraps unpredictably, and there is no visual separation between rows. The PDF output from this tool solves each of these problems. Columns are sized proportionally to their content, cell borders provide clear boundaries, and alternating row backgrounds reduce the chance of reading across to the wrong line in a wide table. The result is a document that looks like it came from a professional reporting tool rather than a raw data export.
      </p>

      <h3>When Spreadsheet Sharing Is Not Appropriate</h3>
      <p>
        There are many situations where sending a spreadsheet is the wrong choice. Editable files can be altered before being forwarded, which creates version control and trust issues. Spreadsheets may contain hidden sheets, formulas, or metadata that you do not intend to share. Some recipients lack spreadsheet software entirely, particularly on mobile devices where CSV rendering is inconsistent. PDF eliminates all of these concerns: the document is read-only, contains exactly the data you chose to include, and renders identically on every device. For board reports, client deliverables, audit documentation, and any situation where data integrity matters, PDF is the appropriate delivery format.
      </p>

      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

      <h3>How does CSV to PDF conversion work in the browser?</h3>
      <p>
        The tool parses your CSV into rows and columns, then builds a PDF document with a formatted table. It draws headers, alternating row colors, and handles pagination automatically. The entire process runs in JavaScript with no server calls.
      </p>

      <h3>Will my CSV data be uploaded to a server?</h3>
      <p>
        No. Everything happens locally in your browser. Your CSV data never leaves your device. You can disconnect from the internet and the tool still works.
      </p>

      <h3>What delimiters does this tool support?</h3>
      <p>
        Comma, tab, semicolon, and pipe. Select the correct one before parsing so that columns split at the right positions.
      </p>

      <h3>Can I mark the first row as a header?</h3>
      <p>
        Yes. Check the "First row is header" checkbox. Header rows render with bold text and a distinct background color in the PDF for easier reading.
      </p>

      <h3>Is there a size limit?</h3>
      <p>
        The tool handles thousands of rows comfortably with automatic pagination. The practical limit depends on browser memory. For datasets exceeding 100,000 rows, consider a desktop tool.
      </p>

